<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Chicken Note</div>
<div class="nbunit" id="edn395">  395  Thomas Cowan (in a private communication) suggests that the piece is a simple conventional contrast of the philosophies of Idealism and Realism (modern style) in a religious setting. The druid he sees as a form of Duns Scotus, reading &lsquo;Entis-onton&rsquo; as &lsquo;Being of being&rsquo; or God. (In this context see <a name="n03095b" href="../fnbs/n03all.htm#n03095b">N3 (VI.B.3):095(b)</a> and <a name="n12048b" href="../fnbs/n12all.htm#n12048b">N12 (VI.B.14):048(b)</a>). &lsquo;Balenoarch&rsquo; he reads as another God symbol, Melville's great white whale. &lsquo;And,&rsquo; he writes, &lsquo;of course <cite>FW</cite> accepts them all: the day (sun) religions and the night (northern forest) religions. The theme is that <cite>FW</cite> bets on all of them. The volume must be saved though Paradise is lost.&rsquo;  </div>
